{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Era is an essential G-protein in Escherichia coli identified originally as a homologue protein to Ras (E. coli Ras-like protein), which contains a N-terminal GTPase domain followed by an RNA-binding KH domain, that plays a role in ribosome biogenesis. It binds to GTP/GDP and has GTPase activity. It specifically bind to 16S rRNA and serves as a chaperone for processing and maturation of 16S rRNA. GTP binding is required for RNA recognition, which in turn, stimulates the GTP-hydrolyzing activity. ERA is also a checkpoint for assembly of the 30S ribosomal subunit [[cite:PUB00007879], [cite:PUB00055805]]. ERAL1, the homologue in humans, is a mitochondrial RNA chaperone involved in the assembly of the 28S small mitochondrial ribosomal subunit. It binds the 12S mitochondrial rRNA to a 33 nucleotide section delineating the 3' terminal stem-loop region [[cite:PUB00150959], [cite:PUB00150960]]. Mutations in this protein leads to Perrault syndrome, a rare recessive disorder characterised by ovarian dysgenesis and sensorineural deafness [[cite:PUB00150958]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>This entry also includes Origin-associated GTP-binding protein OapA, also known as ArvA, encoded by oapA gene which is part of the three-gene cluster oapABC (origin-associated proteins), involved in generation of extracellular vesicles (arv, archaeal vesiculating GTAse). OapA/ArvA has been described as an archaeal vesiculating GTPase that regulates vesicle production [[cite:PUB00154442], [cite:PUB00154443]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "3iev", "name" "Crystal Structure of ERA in Complex with MgGNP and the 3' End of 16S rRNA"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR027417", "name" "P-loop containing nucleoside triphosphate hydrolase", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR42698" "GTPASE ERA"}, "hamap" {"MF_0